---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
---

<Base title="Framer Motion vs CSS Animations: Why I Switched">
  <Header />
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 font-mono">
    <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground mb-8 inline-block">← back to blog</a>

    <header class="mb-8">
      <h1 class="text-2xl font-normal mb-2">Framer Motion vs CSS Animations: Why I Switched</h1>
      <time class="text-xs text-muted-foreground" datetime="2025-11-04">November 4, 2025</time>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>For years, I animated everything with CSS. It's fast, it's simple, and it works everywhere.</p>
      <p>Then I tried <strong>Framer Motion</strong>, and I can't go back.</p>

      <h2>What CSS Does Well</h2>
      <p>CSS animations are perfect for simple transitions:</p>
      <pre><code>.button {'{'}
  transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
{'}'}

.button:hover {'{'}
  background-color: blue;
{'}'}</code></pre>

      <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>✅ Fast (GPU accelerated)</li>
        <li>✅ Simple syntax</li>
        <li>✅ No JavaScript required</li>
        <li>✅ Works everywhere</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>❌ Limited control (can't respond to scroll, gestures, etc.)</li>
        <li>❌ No exit animations (how do you animate on unmount?)</li>
        <li>❌ Keyframes are verbose</li>
        <li>❌ Hard to orchestrate (staggered animations, sequences)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What Framer Motion Adds</h2>
      <p>Framer Motion is a React animation library that makes complex animations feel simple.</p>

      <h3>1. Declarative Syntax</h3>
      <p>Instead of keyframes, you declare what you want:</p>
      <pre><code>&lt;motion.div
  initial={'{'}{'{'} opacity: 0, y: 20 {'}'}{'}'}
  animate={'{'}{'{'} opacity: 1, y: 0 {'}'}{'}'}
  transition={'{'}{'{'} duration: 0.8 {'}'}{'}'}
&gt;
  Hello, world!
&lt;/motion.div&gt;</code></pre>

      <h3>2. Exit Animations</h3>
      <p>With CSS, you can't animate on unmount. With Framer Motion, you can using <code>AnimatePresence</code> and <code>exit</code> props.</p>

      <h3>3. Scroll-Driven Animations</h3>
      <p>Want to fade content as the user scrolls? With CSS, you need IntersectionObserver + JavaScript. Framer Motion gives you <code>useScroll</code> and <code>useTransform</code> hooks.</p>

      <h3>4. Staggered Animations</h3>
      <p>CSS can't easily stagger child animations. Framer Motion makes it trivial with <code>staggerChildren</code> in variant transitions.</p>

      <h3>5. Gesture Support</h3>
      <p>Drag, hover, tap — all built in with <code>whileHover</code>, <code>whileTap</code>, and <code>drag</code> props.</p>

      <h3>6. Layout Animations</h3>
      <p>The holy grail: animating between layout changes. Just add <code>layout</code> to a <code>motion.div</code> and it smoothly morphs between states.</p>

      <h2>The Trade-offs</h2>
      <p><strong>Bundle Size:</strong> CSS is ~0 KB; Framer Motion is ~35 KB gzipped. For apps where animation quality matters, it's worth it.</p>
      <p><strong>Performance:</strong> Both are GPU-accelerated and hit 60 FPS. Framer Motion has slightly more overhead but it's negligible.</p>

      <h2>When to Use Each</h2>
      <p><strong>Use CSS for:</strong> simple hover effects, state transitions, bundle-critical sites, non-React projects.</p>
      <p><strong>Use Framer Motion for:</strong> complex orchestrations, exit animations, scroll-driven effects, gesture interactions, layout animations, React apps where UX matters.</p>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>CSS animations are great for simple transitions. But when you want your React app to feel <strong>magical</strong>, Framer Motion is worth the bundle size.</p>
    </div>

    <footer class="mt-12 border-t border-border pt-8">
      <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground">← back to all posts</a>
    </footer>
  </article>
</Base>
